Patch Set 5:Looks great, but there were some bugs and tweaks that are needed.Default should be the first entry in the submenu menu.If set to notebookbar, restarting LO wont show notebookbar and changing it to another mode and then back to notebookbar wont make it appear.If notebookbar is enabled, .uno:AvailableToolbars should be disabled.If notebookbar isnt enabled, .uno:Notebookbar should be disabled.For default mode, if the sidebar is opened/closed/only showing the 'show' arrow button, it should be opened only showing the tab bars (what it looks like when you open writer with a cleared profile).For single toolbar mode, the sidebar should be enabled but collapsed only showing the 'show' arrow button, the toolbar icons need to be changed to small if they are set to automatic and the icon style should be changed to sifr if set to automatic. this means that before the activation of single toolbar mode, the icon size and style needs to be preserved in the user profile for non-single toolbar mode, as well as saving it for when exiting single toolbar mode so it can be restored when returning to single toolbar mode. In this mode, all contextual toolbar should be disabled (https://bugs.documentfoundation.org/show_bug.cgi?id=92218#c13).For sidebar mode, the sidbear should be fully opened whatever state it is in and set to the properties tab.For notebookbar mode, the sidebar should be collapsed to show the 'show' arrrow button, similar to single toolbar mode.

Patch Set 2:> Note that some sub-menus are implemented as separate popup menu > controllers, and as such populated only upon menu activation. So if > you really need the full menu structure without executing the vcl > menu, you should at least do a fake call to the vcl menu activation > callback. (The other alternative would be to change > ResourceMenuController to create the MenuBarManager instance > earlier for this case, and then change also MenuBarManager::FillMenuManager > to create the controllers).I opted for the first one: doing a fake call, and that seemed to have done the trick. >  > But be aware that some popup menu controllers don't use standart > dispatch command for their items, as they implement them > internally. So the approach of "get the .uno command from the menu > structure, and later execute it" won't work for such cases.I guess we would deal with that later.Thanks for your pointers and suggestions. Saved me some time looking here and there and then realizing :-)

Patch Set 1:To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous commit. Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 1:> To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving > the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes > it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then > you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous > commit.Git commit --amend is a much easier way to do that.iow checkout your gerrit patchdo the modificationscommit them using --amendgit push origin HEAD:refs/for/master Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed > commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new > thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1The patch looks completely reasonable from the POV of the current state of the code. However, code archaeology suggests that merge commit 67d2af6fac2d9bad52a6b1f6e0cbd1229eb88a42 erroneously removed the call to "ImplUpdate" in MoveItem, since that line is present in BOTH parents of that merge. The "if ( nNewPos < nPos )" seems to be done for the sake of the ImplUpdate, to set the argument it will be called with. It looks reasonable, since the call is made with the default value of bDirect==false, then ImplUpdate updates *all* columns after its first argument (its argument inclusive). So it is essentially called with ::std::min(nPos, nNewPos).So it seems to me that we should rather fix the error in bd24a310be1459510b760b812838cb87923853c5 of using "nPos" instead of "nNewPos" in the second call of ::std::advance (the one before insert), but leave the "if ( nNewPos < nPos )" and reinsert the "ImplUpdate(nPos, ...)".Kendy, I know it is far away, but would you agree with my analysis of your merge commit?Julien, could you try out my suggestion above and test its effects, if the behaviour is good, the bug is still fixed, no other obvious bug is introduced, etc? Thanks in advance.

Is the patch ready for review ? or should I wait for another hour for version n+1 ?iow:In a single patch: do one thing. Upload to gerrit when you think it is ready for review, ie ready, you think, to be merged.Review takes time too.. and every time you upload a new version it essentially invalidate the review done on the previous versionI'm encouraged by your patch.. there are good stuff in there.I'm just trying to adjust the process to make processing these patches easier for all involved :-)

Patch Set 3:Hi Kendy,> I wonder - do we have to introduce a new flag?Of course. In some case it is useful to differentiate focusing caused by F6 or TAB. e.g. in BackingWindow::GetFocus(), GETFOCUS_F6 + !GETFOCUS_FORWARD -> grab focus to thumbnailview while GETFOCUS_TAB -> nothing> Also about removing if(GETFOCUS_TAB & GetGetFocusFlags()) - what now happens when you click there; won't it lead to extra focusing and unfocusing? Or is that unrelated?Yes, you are right. I will revert this change and will add a more explicit solution which will select item just when it is actually necessary. Unfortunately ImplGrabFocus() can't be used outside vcl, which would be a simple way (e.g. using ImplGrabFocus(GETFOCUS_F6) inside BackingWindow too).> The rest is nitpicking :-) - if we really need GETFOCUS_F6, it should be 0x0800, not 0x1000.Are you sure? I just look these GETFOCUS_ flags are defined in this way leaving out 0x0008, 0x0080 and I thought maybe somewhere these flags are used in a special way (e.g. some special bit operation) which makes it necessary.> PreNotify() should return true's, not 1's.Oh, yes. This is the result of new bool improvements. :)

Patch Set 1:removing commented sections is usually rather safe -- cherry-picking is somewhat robust against that. For blank lines, there is no convention on how many we should have were, so this might easily lead to a fight over that (and we shouldnt bother with that then). Patch Set 1:Called functions: probably setFloat / setDouble / setInt / setLong / ... or updateFloat / updateDouble / updateInt / updateLong / ...From the point of view of the driver, it should provide all of those, and the calling code chooses which one to call. Calling code can not only be LibreOffice C++ code, but also user macros, so it cannot be predicted what choice is made.When you create a table and select a DECIMAL or NUMERIC field type, don't you have the following field properties, including "Decimal places"?Entry requires: Length: Decimal places:Default value:Format example:The rounding may be because the driver tells the rest of LibreOffice that 0 decimal places are allowed. Or it may be in the configuration of the UI element. Create a form, and edit the properties of the form control: do you use a formatted field or a numeric field? In a numeric field you can set the decimal accuracy. Check what is put there.When all else fails, I single-step in a debugger from the control's "write to the database calls" into the different layers. But that is a bit heavy-weight :)

Patch Set 1:Wrt. the starvation - actually that was due to the logging; we have so much debugging stuff that it was blocking considerably when writing to the console, making the queue grow.  Without that, all works fine even with the unmodified TileQueue :-)But I worked on the TileQueue too - it seems unnecessary to do all the priority shuffling when inserting, when the prioritization changes with every view switch, and instead do it only when the tile is requested - which seems to work nicely.Wrt. an own queue for tiles - that is exactly the thing that makes the synchronzation hard, as then it is necessary to synchronize between those 2 queues; which in turn kills all the advantage of 2 queues :-)Wrt. PNG compression; if we want to thread it, then let's thread just the compression - that'll make it local, more maintainable, and we can go with as many threads there as we wish (for just the PNG compression piece of code).Wrt. the 342125b8ea - thanks for that!  Unfortunately that again just adds code :-(Either way, please check https://cgit.freedesktop.org/libreoffice/online/log/?h=private/kendy/tilesandcallbacks , I'd really like to get that in...  I've tested it with several people in a session, and it performed pretty well thanks to all your work I was able to build on.

Patch Set 6:Oliver, I forgot to mention that, while this fix makes "Further comments on page <pagefield + n>." *possible*, it would require the user to go into that particular page number field and set the offset. That matches Microsoft Word's offset behavior. Offset is never globally applied across fields. It is applied manually to individual fields. A footer is just the most common instance (at which point, the one instance of the page number is offset on all footers because of the footer's functionality, not the page number's functionality).Whether we eventually abandon this or not (see immediately prior comment), I'll address your inline comment. Good catch!

Patch Set 2:Apologies for my late response on this issue. The following is my rationale for reverting strdup back into PL_strdup:--https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Projects/NSPR/About_NSPR"Memory managementNSPR provides API to perform the basic malloc, calloc, realloc and free functions. Depending on the platform, the functions may be implemented almost entirely in the NSPR runtime or simply shims that call immediately into the host operating system's offerings."-> thus replacing PL_strdup with strdup may cause different results on different platforms--https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Projects/NSPR/Reference/PL_strdup"Returns a pointer to a new memory node in the NSPR heap containing a copy of a specified string.Syntax#include <plstr.h>char *PL_strdup(const char *s);NotesThe memory allocated by PL_strdup should be freed with PL_strfree."--http://linux.die.net/man/3/strdup"DescriptionThe strdup() function returns a pointer to a new string which is a duplicate of the string s. Memory for the new string is obtained with malloc(3), and can be freed with free(3)."-> there is no guarantee that memory on the heap used by strdup (i.e. the heap used by malloc) can be freed using PL_strfree.--Due to these concerns, I would like to request for this change be reopened and re-evaluated. Thank you for your patience on this issue.

Patch Set 1:> codify in UR that on non-Windows wchar_t is 32-bit and represents UTF-32 code unitsWell, that's an implementation "bug". When LibreOffice is ported to a platform where it is not the case, the implementation can be updated for this platform. Or we could implement this function in a more portable way, for example using iconv (but polishing the code to fix the memory leak and all that):static iconv_t cnv = iconv_open("UTF-16", "WCHAR_T");sal_Unicode *buf=calloc(len, 2*sizeof(sal_Unicode))size_t cnvlen =  sizeof(2*sal_Unicode*len)const size_t cps = iconv(cnv, &str, &len, &buf, &cnvlen)rtl_uStringbuffer_insert( &pData, &nCapacity, getLength(), buf, cps );I actually think implementing this feature in a robust way it would be a service to C++ extensions (even if it does not get used much within LibreOffice).As far as the needs of connectivity/odbc are concerned, I'm happy with the solution suggested by email.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1(1 comment)Hi Yogesh, thanks for looking into this.I was worried about the change to wrtw8sty.cxx so I had a bit of a look at the bug myself to understand it better.  I found two different issues which contribute:- the import from docx appears to have a bug which is at play here: when I open the docx in LibreOffice I see that the first page footer has wrong spacing. This affects the export code which tries to join chained page styles into a single word section if they match.  The import bug means that they do not match, so it will try to export this as two different word sections.- however some code recently added to ww8/ww8atr.cxx in a31fbb53dba7 prevents the output of a new section at the page break in this case, as the paragraph on the first page is empty             if( isTextNodeEmpty )                bNewPageDesc = false;So I think these are the two issues that need to be addressed, rather than the change proposed in this item.  Fixing either one of them will solve the reported issue for this document, but it would be great to fix both.

Patch Set 2: Do not submitThanks for tackling this issue ! I have a few comments however:It seems to me that using isalpha / isprint on string characters like this is a particularly horrible way to achieve this :-)To copy/paste a similar chunk of text twice like that is rather poor style - in programming for maintainability the aim is always to minimise the number of new lines we add: to maximise the sharing of lines of code etc.As such - I'd really strongly prefer as much of the if (rtl) { } cases to be shared with the non-rtl cases - can we not setup variables that alter the order of iteration / layout placement / rendering in advance and then use them in a shared block later ?When we do:+            // this code are for reverse the number of sildes in TitleThe title we have there seems to come from:void PresenterPaneBase::PaintBorder (const awt::Rectangle& rUpdateBox)...            mxBorderPainter->paintBorder(                mxPaneId->getResourceURL(),                mxBorderCanvas,                aLocalBorderBox,                rUpdateBox,                msTitle);msTitle - can we not translate translate and/or generate that msTitle (SetTitle?) in the first instance ?Is that created from a template in:void PresenterController::UpdatePaneTitles (void)if so - we should fix it there in just one place :-)That template prolly comes from the (localised?) configuration and just needs changing there ?Anyhow - thanks again for looking at this - with a few tweaks (as above) I think we can make it a lot sweeter.Thanks !

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit thisHi Mathias,first thanks for your patch. It is great start; Well, it does some non-standard things. I suggest to re-shufle it a bit :-)1. You already mentioned that you were unsure about    downloading the files inside configure. I suggest to   do it using the download script.   You might already see the many @FILENAME@ entries in   ooo.lst.in. They are optional. If you do not define such    variable in configure, it will be empty in the generated    ooo.lst file and it will not be downloaded.2. If you use download, it will get the files into the   $TARFILE_LOCATION instead of $SRC_ROOT/moz/zipped.      I suggest to modify the related makefiles in "moz"    module to find the .zip archives in $TARFILE_LOCATION   Note that this approach follows the current trends.   In the past, we copied many 3rd party tarballs into   the related build subdirectories. We do not longer   do it. We already updated most makefiles to unpack the    tarballs directly from the $TARFILE_LOCATION.   3. I suggest to do not copy the dlls in configure because    it is not typical. Instead, I suggest to define variables   that will point to the files. Then you could copy the   files in the makefile that need to use the dlls.4. Please, do not remove the TABs from configure.in from    lines 4469-4515. These lines are copied into "Makefile"    that is later tested. TABs are important in Makefiles,   so your change breaks this test.Thanks a lot for working on it. Feel free to ask if you are in doubts.
